{\fs21 Proprioception \line and Motor Control}{\fs21 \par }\pard\plain \s12\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\f5\fs20\b\i0\expnd-1\expndtw-4 Proprioception}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4  refers to our sensation and perception of limb, trunk, and head position and movement.}
{\*\cs49\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4\super 1}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4  Although it is often overlooked as one of our basic senses, proprioception is sensory information transmitted to the central nervous system about such movement characteristics as direction, location in space, velocity, and muscle activation. In closed-loop models of movement control, proprioceptive feedback plays a significant role, whereas in open-loop models, central commands control movement without involving proprioceptive feedback. Questions about whether we can control movements without proprioceptive feedback, and what role \u173 ?
proprioceptive feedback plays in the control of \u173 ?coordinated movement, have intrigued movement scientists for many years (see \u173 ?
Willingham, 1998, p.\u8239 ?574 for a brief historical review).\par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 Researchers have taken a variety of experimental approaches to determine the role of proprioception in controlling coordinated movement. We discuss a few of these to introduce you to the current thinking about this issue. However, before considering proprioception\rquote s role in motor control, we will take a brief look at the neural basis of proprioception.\par }
\pard\plain \s13\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb200\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
