{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 The CNS receives proprioceptive \u173 ?information from }{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw4 afferent neural pathways that begin in }
{\*\cs50\fs20\b\i0\expnd1\expndtw4 pro\u173 ?pri\u173 ?}{\*\cs50\fs20\b\i0\expnd-1\expndtw-4 oceptors}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 , which are sensory neurons located in the muscles, tendons, ligaments, and joints. These neurons pick up information about body and limb position and changes in position. There are several types of proprioceptors, each of which detects \u173 ?
specific characteristics of body and limb position and movement.}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4  We focus on the muscle spindles, which detect changes in muscle length, the Golgi-tendon organs, which detect changes in muscle tension, and the joint receptors, which detect changes in joint movement.\par }
\pard\plain \s16\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb120\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
