{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Vision is the result of the sensory receptors of the eyes receiving and transmitting wavelengths of light to the visual cortex of the brain by way of sensory neurons known as the optic nerve. In a section about the eye in their neuroscience book, Bear, Connors, and Paradiso (2001) state, \ldblquote the eye acts like a camera, forming crisp, clear images of the world. . . . Like a quality 35-mm camera, the eye automatically adjusts to differences in illumination and automatically focuses itself on objects of interest. The eye has some additional features not yet available on cameras, such as the ability to track moving objects (by eye movement) and the ability to keep its transparent surfaces clean (by tears and blinking)\rdblquote  (p. 281).}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \par }\pard\plain \s16\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb200\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs51\f7\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd-1\expndtw-4\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Basic anatomy of the eye.}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 \u8194\'20As illustrated in figure 6.6, \line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 the human eye is a fluid-filled ball with distinct components. The }
{\f5\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw0 cornea}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  is the most anterior component. It is a clear surface that allows light to enter the eye and serves as an important part of \line the eye\rquote s optical system. Because it does not have blood vessels, it can be surgically removed with relative ease and, if necessary, a donated cornea can be transplanted. Behind the cornea are the pupil, iris, and lens. The }
{\f5\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw0 pupil}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  is the opening that lets light into the eye. Its diameter increases and decreases according to the amount of light detected by the eye. You have undoubtedly experienced this when you looked into a mirror and watched the pupil of your eye get larger and smaller depending on the amount of light in the room or shining in your eye. This diameter change is controlled by smooth muscle fibers }
{\f6\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw0 within the iris}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 . The }{\f5\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw0 iris}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0
 \u173 ?surrounds the pupil and provides the eye its color. The }{\f5\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw0 lens}{\f6\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw0
,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  which sits just behind the iris, is a transparent structure that is responsible for allowing the eye to focus at various distances. The lens is held in place by the zonular fibers }
{\f6\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw0 and its shape is controlled by the ciliary muscles shown in figure 6.6}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 . The sclera, which makes up 80 percent of the eye, surrounds these structures. The anterior portion of this firm white capsule forms what we commonly call the \ldblquote white}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 \rdblquote  of the eye. The sclera functions to help maintain the shape of the eye and protect the eye\rquote s inner structure. It also is an attachment site for the extrinsic eye muscles responsible for eye movement. The eye contains two chambers of fluid: }
{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 aqueous humor}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  is a clear fluid that fills the chamber between the cornea and lens, and }
{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 vitreous humor}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  is a viscous substance that fills the chamber between the lens and the back wall of the eye.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 \par }\pard\plain \s16\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs51\f7\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 The neural components of the eye and vision.}
{\fs20 \u8194\'20}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 The neural aspects of vision begin with the }{\f5\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw0 retina}{\f6\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw0
,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  the structure that lines the back wall of the eye. Although it is part of the eye, the retina is actually an extension of the brain (Widmaier, Raff, & Strang, }
{\f6\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw0 2019}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 ). It contains various types of neurons and photoreceptor cells. The primary components of the retina include the }
{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 fovea centralis,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  where objects seen in central vision are focused (hence the term }
{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 foveal vision}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 ) and is therefore responsible for visual acuity, and the }
{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 optic disk,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  where the axons of the retina\rquote s neurons converge to transmit information to the optic nerve. The retina contains two types of photoreceptor cells called }
{\f5\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw0 rods}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  and }{\f5\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw0 cones}{\f6\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw0
,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  which }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 play important roles in vision. Three roles are particularly relevant for the performance of motor skills. One }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 role }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 is that rods respond to low levels of light (which makes them responsible for night vision); cones respond only to bright light. Because of the specific levels of light to which they respond,}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  these photoreceptors are the cause of the }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 \ldblquote temporary blindness\rdblquote  experience you have when the lighting in a room changes from very bright to dark. In such a situation the \u173 ?
responsibility for light detection shifts from the cones to the rods, a process that requires a brief amount of time.\par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 A second role for rods and cones relates to their location on the retina. Cones are concentrated at the center, which gives them a critical role in central vision and visual acuity. Rods are located more on the retina periphery and}
{\fs20 ,}{\fs20  therefore}{\fs20 , are}{\fs20  important for peripheral vision. Third, cones play a critical role in color vision.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 \par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 The retina receives light waves from the cornea and lens, where the waves are }{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i refracted}{\fs20 \'d1that is, bent}
{\fs20 \'d1in such a way that an observed image is turned upside down and reversed right to left on the retina. Image size and distance from the eye are determined by the size of the angle the light waves from the image form when they pass through the cornea; there is more bending for bigger and closer images to create larger images on the retina, and less bending for smaller and more distant images to create smaller images on the retina. This \u173 ?
distinction is important for motor \u173 ?control in situations in which }{\fs20 \line }{\fs20 a person must make contact with or intercept a moving object, which we will discuss further later in this chapter and in chapter 7.\par }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 Axons of neurons in the retina called ganglion cells form the }{\f5\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw2 optic nerve}
{\*\cs50\f6\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw2 ,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2  which is cranial nerve II and serves as the means of information transmission from the eye to the brain. As you can see in figure 6.7}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 , the optic nerves from the two eyes meet near the base of the brain and form the }{\f5\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw2
optic \u173 ?chiasm}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 , where the nerve fibers either continue to the same side of the brain or cross over to the opposite side of the brain and continue to the visual cortex at the back of the brain\rquote s cortex. Whether optic nerve fibers cross at the optic chiasm or change to the \u173 ?
opposite side of the brain depends on the visual field on the retina from which the fibers originate. The optic nerve fibers project to several brain structures, with the largest number passing through the lateral geniculate nucleus of the thalamus.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 \par }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 The }{\f5\fs20\b\i0\expnd-1\expndtw-4 visual field}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4
 refers to the image or scene being viewed. As illustrated in }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 figure 6.7, each eye sees a portion of the image or scene. One portion, referred to as the }
{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-4 nasal part of the visual field,}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4  is detected by the inner halves of each eye, while the }
{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-4 temporal part of the visual field}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4  is detected by the outer halves of each eye. The optic nerve fibers associated with the nasal part, which is projected through the lens and cornea to the interior side of the retinas, cross over at the optic chiasm to the opposite hemisphere of the cortex while the optic nerve fibers associated with the temporal part pass through the optic chiasm to remain in the same cortex hemisphere. The visual cortex of the brain unites these images in a way that allows us to see three dimensional images. As we will discuss later in this chapter, this }
{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-4 binocular vision}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 \'d1that is, seeing with both eyes\'d1is the basis for our depth perception as we observe the world around us.}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 \par }\pard\plain \s15\f5\fs21\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb390\sa120\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\keepn\caps\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs21 Investigating the Role of Vision in Motor Control\par }\pard\plain \s12\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Researchers use a variety of techniques to study the role of vision in motor control. The most direct technique involves the recording of eye movements as a person performs a skill. Other techniques provide indirect ways to determine how a person uses vision during the performance of a skill. We will briefly discuss these techniques in the following sections.\par }
\pard\plain \s13\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb350\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Eye Movement Recording}{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s12\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 The recording of a person\rquote s eye movements requires }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1
the use of specialized equipment that tracks the movement of the eyes and records where the eyes are \ldblquote looking\rdblquote  at a particular time. A researcher can record the displacement of }
{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-1 foveal vision}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  for a specific time interval, as well as the place and the length of time the person fixates his or her gaze while tracking. One way researchers use this }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \line \u173 ?}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 technique is to have the participant observe a film simulation of a performance situation and then make a response. The movement of the eye is then plotted on the film scene to determine the spatial location of the participant}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \rquote s eye movements (displacement), along with his or her gaze fixation characteristics related to observing the action. A more difficult way to use this procedure is to record eye movements while a person is actually performing a skill in the performance setting. }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 (For a more detailed discussion about the use of eye-movement recordings, see}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 Kredel, Vater, Klostermann, & Hossner, 2017 and}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  Reimer }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1
&}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  Sodhi, 2006}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 .}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 )\par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 An experiment by Williams, Ward, Knowles, and Smeeton (2002) provides a good example of the use of eye movement recordings to investigate the use of vision in the performance of a \u173 ?
motor skill. The experiment compared skilled and less-skilled tennis players as they viewed and \u173 ?responded to action sequences that would occur \line in a tennis match. The players observed videos of near-life-size images of opponents as a means of simulating play during a match. A player\rquote s view was of an opponent positioned midcourt on the other side of the net. The videos presented opponents hitting forehand and backhand shots during match play situations toward the players\rquote  left court, right court, center forecourt, and center backcourt. The players, who each wore an eye movement recording device, were asked to \u173 ?
re\u173 ?spond to each shot as they would in an actual tennis match, which is to respond as quickly and accurately as possible. The results showed that the skilled players spent more time viewing the opponent\rquote s trunk-hip and head-shoulder areas than did the less-skilled players, while the less-skilled players spent more time than the skilled players viewing the opponent\rquote s racquet.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \par }\pard\plain \s13\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Temporal Occlusion Procedure\par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 This procedure is used to prevent an observer from seeing what is going to happen next in an action sequence by stopping a video recording the observer is watching or blocking vision by activating specialized goggles that are worn by the observer. The procedure allows an investigation of the }
{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i amount of time}{\fs20  a person requires to visually detect the environmental context information he or she uses to perform a skill. It is especially useful for skill performance situations in which choices among several movement alternatives must be made, which includes situations such as returning a serve in racquet sports, deciding whether to (and when to) dribble, pass, or shoot in basketball, or deciding when to walk across a busy street.\par }
\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 When film or video is used, the observer is required to make a response as quickly as possible when the recording is stopped at predetermined time points during the action sequence. An excellent and commonly cited example of the use of this procedure is in an experiment by Abernethy and Russell (1987), in which badminton players watched film sequences of a player making different shots. When the film stopped, participants marked their predictions of the landing positions of the shuttle. The film stopped at different times prior to, during, and after shuttle contact. By noting the relationship between the accuracy of a participant\rquote s predicted shuttle landing location and the moment he or she made the decision, the researchers could determine when in the time course of the observed action the participant had visually selected the information needed to make a decision.\par }
\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 Some researchers have used the temporal occlusion procedure to determine when skilled athletes visually detect critical information in dynamic team ball games, such as soccer. In these types of games, successful performance is often dependent on the anticipation of an opponent\rquote s or teammate\rquote s action, such as whether he or she will pass the ball or make a shot at the goal. To assess when players detect this critical information, researchers have presented short video clips that stop at various amounts of time prior to the specific action}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 ;}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 then they}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  ask the player to indicate which type of action the player on the video will perform. The general conclusion from this type of research is that the critical information is detected in the final few seconds before the specific action (e.g., pass or shot at goal) (see North & Williams, 2008).}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 \par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 The other}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  temporal occlusion procedure involves the use of specially prepared visual occlusion spectacles, such as those seen in figure 6.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 8}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 . The lenses contain liquid crystals that the experimenter can activate or deactivate to cause the lenses to be transparent or occluded. The change in the state of the lenses occurs very quickly (}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 1\'d05}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  msec). A benefit of the lenses is that they change the visual condition almost instantaneously without the eyes requiring the typical amount of time to adapt to changes \u173 ?
between light and dark conditions. The visual \u173 ?occlusion lenses provide an advantage over the procedure of stopping a video or film by allowing researchers to have research participants perform skills in their typical environmental context.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 One limitation with this technique is that researchers have typically triggered the visual occlusion spectacles using a manual button press. This limitation has recently been overcome with the development of a laser curtain that is triggered automatically when a performer}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \rquote }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 s movement distorts the lasers (Brenton, M}{\f9\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1
\'9f}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 ller, Rhodes, & Finch, 2018). With this set up, researchers now can more precisely occlude vision at specific time points within an opponent}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \rquote }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 s action.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 A question that arises from the use of the temporal occlusion technique in laboratory environments is this: Are the results obtained from this procedure consistent with the way people use vision when performing the same skills in real-world environments? Two experiments by Farrow, Abernethy, and }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\u173 ?}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 Jackson (2005) addressed this question using novice and skilled tennis players. Results indicated that the \u173 ?
laboratory-based temporal occlusion technique generalizes very well to real-world environments.\par }\pard\plain \s13\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Event Occlusion Procedure\par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 This procedure}{\fs20 , also referred to as the }{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i spatial occlusion procedure,}{\fs20  involves editing film or video recordings to occlude parts of the environmental context or the performer. The }
{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i event occlusion procedure }{\fs20 is used to identify the specific visual information a person uses to make a response. Parts of each frame of film or video are masked so that the observer cannot see selected parts of the action. Figure 6.9 presents an example of this procedure, taken from the second part of the Abernethy and Russell (1987) study. In their experiment, participants predicted the landing location of the shuttle when they could not see the arm and racquet, racquet, head, or legs of the person hitting the shuttle. The logic of this approach is that if the person performs worse without being able to see a specific feature of the opponent\rquote s action, then that feature includes the \u173 ?
visual information the \u173 ?person uses to determine the location of the shot.}{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s15\f5\fs21\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb235\sa120\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\keepn\caps\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs21 The Role of Vision \line in Motor Control\par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Vision plays many roles in the control of coordinated movement. We will consider some of these roles in the following sections by discussing them in the context of several issues that researchers have investigated. }
{\fs20 We will further explore the role }{\fs20 of vision in motor control in chapter 7 by }{\fs20\u173 ?}{\fs20 discussing its involvement in the control of specific motor skills, such as prehension, locomotion, and catching and striking objects.}
