{\fs20 Monocular versus Binocular Vision\par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 One of the questions researchers have investigated concerning the role of vision in motor control relates }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 to }{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 the use of monocular (i.e., one eye) }{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2\u173 ?}
{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 compared to }{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 \line }{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-4
binocular (i.e., two eyes) vision}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4  to perform motor skills.}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4  Research evidence (e.g., Coull et al., 2000; Goodale & }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4\u173 ?}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 Servos, 1996; Servos, 2000; Zago, McIntyre, Senot, & Lacquanti, 2009) has shown that the motor control system operates more effectively and efficiently when it receives vis}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 ual information from }{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-3 both}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  eyes. Although people can reach and pick up objects when the use of only one eye is available, the accuracy and efficiency of the movement decrease as the distance to the object increases. Experiments (e.g., Coull }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 \line }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 et al., 2000}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 ; Grant, 2015}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3
) that have shown this influence of distance provide \u173 ?support for the view that binocular vision is important for }{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-3
depth perception.}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 \par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 Monocular vision appears to interfere with movement planning and movement execution}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4
. }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 \line }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 When only one eye is available}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4  during movement }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 planning}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 , people consistently underestimate the distance to objects and the size of the objects. These underestimates are not corrected during the movement }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 itself, which }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 also }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 indicates the need for binocular }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 vision to provide important }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 information for correcting }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4
errors in limb movement}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 . Research investigations of these problems have shown errors in movement kinematics during the movement (e.g., Bingham, 2005; Jackson, Newport, & Shaw, 2002) and movement end-point accuracy (e.g., Chapman, Scally, & Buckley, }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 \line }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 2012}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 ;}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4  Heath, Neely, & Krigolson, 2008). Interestingly, when people are not permitted to use binocular \u173 ?
vision and must reach for and grasp an object using monocular vision, they will move their heads in a manner that enables them to obtain more accurate information about the size of an object and the distance to it (see Marotta, Kruyer, & Goodale, 1998).}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4  }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 Reaching with monocular vision can be improved when proprioceptive information is concurrently available to help localize a target in space. For example, participants performed a bead threading task onto a vertical needle faster and more accurately when they grasped the needle with their other hand than when the needle was freestanding (Tugac, Gonzalez, Noguchi, & Niechwiej-Szwedo, 2019). }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 \par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Binocular vision also provides better movement control than monocular vision for other motor skills, such as locomotion and intercepting moving objects. For example, research evidence shows that when a person is walking along a pathway and must step over an obstacle, binocular vision is important for the detection of the }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 three dimensional}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  \u173 ?characteristics of the environment needed to initiate and step over the obstacle (Patla, Niechwiej, Racco, & Goodale, 2002). This information enables the person to move the stepping leg accurately to clear the obstacle while stepping over it. Here again we see evidence for the importance of binocular vision for visual depth perception.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \par }{\fs20 Finally, binocular vision also provides important information to help us intercept moving objects. \line An example of research evidence supporting this role for binocular vision was reported in an experiment in which participants used monocular or binocular vision to hit a moving object (Scott, van der Kamp, Savelsbergh, Oudejans, & Davids, 2004). Results showed that the participants using monocular \u173 ?
vision missed the object more frequently, indicating that binocular vision provides important information to guide interceptive actions in skills such as hitting a moving ball.\par }
\pard\plain \s13\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Central and Peripheral Vision\par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Another question of interest relates to the }{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 roles of central and peripheral vision }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 in the control of movement}{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 .}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  }{\f5\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-2
Central vision}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 , which is sometimes called }{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 foveal}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
 vision, detects information only in the middle 2 to 5 degrees of the visual field. }{\f5\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-2 Peripheral vision}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 , on the other hand, detects information in the visual field outside these limits. For most people, the visual field extends approximately 200 degrees horizontally and 160 degrees vertically. The current understanding is that each makes specific contribu}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-5 tions. }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 To demonstrate how central and peripheral vision each provide distinct information for motor control, we will consider research related to two types of motor skills related to everyday living: reaching and grasping an object, and locomotion. \par }
\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 First, imagine yourself sitting at a table with the intent to pick up a cup sitting on the table. In this situation, as you prepare to move}
{\fs20 ,}{\fs20  central vision fixates on the cup to obtain information on its size, shape, and distance from your present position. As you begin to reach for the cup your moving hand is seen by peripheral vision, which will provide online feedback to guide the reaching and grasping of the cup. As your hand nears the cup, central vision becomes critical again for providing information needed to actually grasp the cup.\par }
\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 There is an abundance of research evidence to support the roles of central and peripheral vision in the prehension task situation just described. For example, an experiment by Sivak and MacKenzie (1990) showed that when participants could use only central vision to reach and grasp an object, the organization and control of the movement to the object was affected, but not the grasping of the \line object. When the researchers blocked the partici\u8209 ?
\line }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 pants}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 \rquote  use of central vision, which meant they could use only peripheral vision for reaching and grasping an object, problems occurred with both the transport and grasp phases. }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \par }{\fs20 The results of the Sivak and MacKenzie experiment match those reported in other research by showing the distinct roles played by central and peripheral vision in the control of limb movements, especially those involved in manual aiming and prehension (see Gaveau et al., 2014 and Jeannerod & Marteniuk, 1992, for reviews of this research). }
{\fs20 \par }{\fs20 Central and peripheral vision also play different roles in locomotion. For example, research has shown that when we walk along a pathway, central vision provides information that guides us so that we can stay on the pathway, whereas peripheral vision is important to provide and update our knowledge about the spatial features of the walking environment, such as pathway dropoffs or bumps (Turano, Yu, Hao, & Hicks, 2005). The information received through \u173 ?
peripheral vision during locomotion is particularly important to help people maintain their action goal without being affected by pathway problems, such as obstacles, other people, or irregular steps on a stairway.}
{\*\cs52\f5\fs18\caps0\scaps0\b\i0\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0  \par }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4
In a study that combined prehension and locomotion, Graci (2011) had participants pick up a full glass of water on a table located at the end of their walking path and move the glass to a new location on the table. They performed this task with either full vision of their lower body, the table and glass, and with occluded vision, which prevented them from using peripheral vision to see the table and their lower body when they reached the table. They could always see the glass of water. One of the effects of not having peripheral vision available was the time to contact the glass, which was calculated from the end of their last step until their hand reached the glass, Without the availability of peripheral vision, they increased their time to contact the glass by approximately 40 percent.\par }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 One of the most important sources of information available to peripheral vision for controlling actions is }
{\*\cs50\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 optical flow}{\fs20 .}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  Optical flow refers to the moving pattern of rays of light that strikes the retina of the eye from all parts of the environment. The word \ldblquote flow\rdblquote  is significant because it indicates the dynamic nature of this visually detected information. When our head moves through the environment, whether through head turning, postural sway, or locomotion, our visual system detects and uses patterns of optical flow that covary precisely with the speed and direction of our head motion. Similarly, movement of an object, a person, or a surface provides the visual system with a different pattern of optical flow that specifies the direction and speed with which that particular feature of the environment is moving. Differentiating the various patterns of optical flow allows us to effectively control posture, locomotion, and object manipulation and to coordinate our actions with the regulatory conditions in the environment. (For an excellent review of research concerning optical flow and an \u173 ?
experiment involving the use of optical flow, see \u173 ?Konczak, 1994, and for a review of the development of responsiveness to optical flow, see \u173 ?
Anderson, Campos, & Barbu-Roth, 2004.)}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 \par }\pard\plain \s16\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs51\f7\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw-2\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Two visual systems for motor control.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \u8194\'20The distinctive behavioral roles for central and peripheral \u173 ?vision, along with supporting neurophysiological evidence, have led some researchers to propose that the visual system is actually two anatomical systems that operate in parallel (see Brown, \u173 ?
Halpert, & }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Goodale}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 , 2005, for a more detailed discussion of the two vision systems). Paillard (1980), for example, proposed that a }
{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 kinetic}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  visual channel was respon\u173 ?sible for processing visual information in peripheral \u173 ?
vision. This channel would process high-speed movement information and control limb movement direction. To process visual information in central vision and for slow-speed movements, Paillard proposed a }
{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 static}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  visual channel.}{\*\cs49\fs16\expnd-1\expndtw-3\super 2}{\fs16\expnd-1\expndtw-3
For a review of research that has tested Paillard\rquote s two visual systems model, and two experiments that support and extend this model, see Proteau, Bolvin, Linossier, and Abahnini (2000). And, for a defense of the model, see Milner, Ganel, }
{\fs16\expnd-1\expndtw-3 and}{\fs16\expnd-1\expndtw-3  Goodale (2012). }{\*\cs49\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2\super 2}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
 Other researchers have proposed similar two-\u173 ?channel visual systems but have given them different names. Some examples include the }
{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i focal}{\f6\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw-2  vision system, which is responsible for the detection of static objects by central vision, and the }
{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 ambient}{\f6\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw-2  vision system, which detects objects and movement around us, involving peripheral vision (Trevarthen, 1968); another is }
{\f6\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw-2 the}{\f6\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw-2  }{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 vision-for-perception}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  system, which would be responsible for recognizing and describing what a person is seeing, and the }{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2
vision-for-action}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  system which would be responsible for perceptually guided movements \u173 ?(Brown, Halpert, & Goodale, 2005; Goodale & \u173 ?
Milner, 1992)}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 .\par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 When described in anatomical terms, the two visual systems identified by Goodale and Milner (1992) have been referred to as the }
{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 ventral stream,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  which is used for fine analysis of the visual scene into form, color, and features\'d1in other words, what a person is seeing}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \'d1and the }{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-3 dorsal stream,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  which is responsible for the spatial characteristics of what is seen as well as for guiding movement \line (e.g., }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 Cameron, Franks, Enns, & Chua, 2007; Reed, Klatzky, & Halgren, 2005). As this designation of the two systems suggests, the neural pathways of the two systems are anatomically distinct. To use the Goodale and Milner terms for the two systems, the vision-for-perception system processes visual information via a cortical pathway leading from the primary visual cortex to the temporal lobe, whereas the vision-for-action system routes information from the primary visual cortex to the posterior parietal cortex (Brown, Halpert, & Goodale, 2005; Reed et al., 2005).\par }
{\fs20 One important characteristic of the two systems relates to our conscious awareness of the information detected by each system. We are generally \u173 ?
consciously aware of information detected by the }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 ventral stream, but not of that detected by the dorsal stream. This disassociation leads to some interesting behaviors in patients with damage to the ventral or dorsal stream. For example, a patient with damage to the ventral stream could have no conscious perception of the size or orientation of an object, but could pick up and manipulate the object without any problems (Goodale & Milner, 1992).\par }
\pard\plain \s13\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Perception-Action Coupling: \line The Coordination of Vision and Movement}{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 When you play a video game on your computer and you must move the mouse}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  or joystick}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  quickly and precisely so that the object you control on the screen hits a target, or when you want to quickly unlock the door to your residence, your eyes and hand work together in a coordinated way to allow you to carry out these actions. Similarly, when you want to kick a moving ball or stop it with your foot, your eyes and feet coordinate so that you can successfully carry out the intended action. The spatial and temporal coordination of \u173 ?
vision and the hands or feet in these types of skill performance situations is an example of what is known as perception-\u173 ?
action coupling.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  This means that the visual perception of the object and the limb movement required to achieve the action goal are \ldblquote coupled,\rdblquote  or coordinated, in a way that enables people to perform eye-hand and eye-foot coordination skills. Perception-action coupling is not confined to the hands and feet}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  or to the visual system}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 , but can be seen in any situation where an action, such as posture or locomotion, is coordinated with features of the environment.\par }
\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 One of the ways researchers have determined this coordination characteristic is by pairing the eye movement recording technique, which we discussed in the preceding section, with the motion analysis technique discussed in chapter 2. Although \u173 ?
perception-action coupling can involve any movement (an excellent example is the visual-postural coupling described earlier in Lee & Aronson\rquote s [1974] moving room experiment), we will focus here on the coupling of vision and hand movements.\par }
{\fs20 For eye movement analysis, the characteristic of interest is the }{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i point of gaze,}{\fs20  which is the specific location in the environment on which central }
{\fs20 \line }{\fs20 (i.e., foveal) vision is fixated at any particular moment. For example}{\fs20 ,}{\fs20  to assess the coordination of vision and hand movement to a target, researchers calculate the relationship between the timing and/or location of the termination of the point of gaze with the timing and/or location of the hand movement. If the point of gaze and hand movement are temporally or spatially coupled, the point of gaze should be at a specific location at a consistent proportion of the total movement time and/or distance of the hand movement.\par }
\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 A good example of research evidence that demonstrates the coupling between vision and hand movement is an experiment by Helsen, Elliott, Starkes, and Ricker (1998). Participants moved their index fingers 40 cm to the right from a starting location in front of them to a 1 cm by 2 cm target as fast as \line \u173 ?
possible. Both point of gaze and hand movements tended to undershoot the target and then made one or more corrections to hit the target. The analysis of eye and finger movements showed that the participants typically initiated eye movements approximately 70\u8239 ?
msec }{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 before}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  they began to move their hands from\u8239 ?the start location. The initial eye movement moved the point of gaze very close to the target (about 95 percent of the total distance), after which participants made a second eye movement to correct the undershooting of the first. The point of gaze typically arrived at the target 450 msec }
{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 before}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  the finger, which would allow for inflight hand movement corrections based on visual feedback. The researchers found evidence for }
{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 temporal coupling}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  between the eye movements and hand movements because the completion of the initial eye movement coincided with the timing of the peak acceleration of the hand movement. Evidence for }
{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 spatial coupling}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  was shown by the point of gaze consistently terminating on the target when the hand movement was at 50 percent of the total movement distance.\par }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 Since that experiment, the same researchers (Helsen, Elliott, Starkes, & Ricker, 2000) showed that the initiation of elbow and shoulder movements is also coupled in time with eye and finger movement initiation. The sequence of events was that the eyes moved first, followed by the shoulder, then the elbow, and finally the finger. On every trial for every participant, the point of gaze was on the target long before the hand arrived at the target. }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 Similar coupling effects have been demonstrated for vision and feet during locomotion. For example, researchers have shown that people with vision gaze }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0\u173 ?}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 control deficits exhibit foot lift and stepping problems during stair climbing (DiFabio, Zampieri, & Tuite, 2008). Thus, the}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  results of these experiments and others like them support the importance of vision for picking up critical spatial information to initiate and guide limb movements to a target and to provide spatial and temporal feedback to ensure the accurate arrival of the limb at the target.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 \par }\pard\plain \s13\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 The Amount of Time Needed to Make \line Vision-Based Movement Corrections\par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 An important factor that influences the role of vision in motor control is the amount of time available to use visual feedback to make movement corrections while the movement is in progress. }
{\fs20 Recall from our discussion in chapter 5 of the closed-loop motor control system that feedback can be used to make movement }
{\fs20 corrections only when the person has sufficient time to detect a movement error and modify the movement. This means there is a minimum total movement time requirement in order for the performer to be able to use visual feedback to correct movement errors prior to the completion of the movement.\par }
\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 The important question here is: }{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-1 What is the minimum amount of time required}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  }{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i for movement corrections}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  to be carried out on the basis of visual feedback? Researchers have been attempting to answer this question for more than 100 years, beginning with research by Woodworth in 1899. The most vigorous effort to investigate this question \u173 ?
occurred in the latter part of the twentieth century, beginning with an influential experiment by Keele and Posner }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1
\line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 in 1968. Unfortunately, all this research effort has not provided us with a precise answer to the question (see Carlton, 1992 and \u173 ?
Elliott, Helsen, & Chua, 2001, for excellent reviews of this research). Part of the problem is that different experimental procedures have resulted in a variety of time estimates for the processing of visual feedback.\par }
{\fs20 The most common experimental procedure has been to have people perform manual aiming movements with different goal movement times. On some trials, the lights would go out just as the person \u173 ?
began to move, whereas on other trials the lights \u173 ?remained on. The logic to this procedure was that if visual feedback were necessary, aiming accuracy would decrease with the lights out because the person could not see the target and therefore would not be able to use visual feedback. When participants did not know when the lights would be on or off, the amount of time to process visual feedback was estimated to be between 190 and 260 msec. However, later experiments used the same lights-\u173 ?
on-or-off technique, but participants knew when they would perform under each condition (e.g., Elliott & Allard, 1985; Zelaznik, Hawkins, & \u173 ?
Kisselburgh, 1983). This advance knowledge indicated that visual feedback could be used in less than 100 msec.}{\fs20 \par }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3
Other experimental procedures have led re\u173 ?search\u173 ?}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 ers to conclude that visual feedback can be processed }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 in amounts of time that are faster or slower than those estimated by the lights-on-or-off procedure.}{\fs20
 \line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 These have included such procedures as distorting the visual information by having people wear prism glasses (e.g., Smith & Bowen, 1980, \u173 ?
estimated the time to be about 150 msec); moving the target location after the person initiated a movement to a target (e.g., Brenner & Smeets, 1997, 2009, \u173 ?
estimated the time to be between 110 and 150 msec); and preventing visual feedback for portions of the distance to the target (e.g., Spijkers & Lochner, 1994, estimated the time to be about 135\u8239 ?
msec).}{\fs20 \par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 Although it is not possible to establish an exact minimum amount of time required to use visual feedback to enable movement corrections, it \u173 ?
ap\u173 ?pears that an estimate of a range from }{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw2 100 to 160 msec}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2  is reasonable to capture movement correction limits for most motor skills. However, it is important to note that the minimum amount of time could be faster in situations where the person is anticipating the need to make a movement correction.\par }
