{\*\cs51\f7\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Application to real-world motor skill perfor\u173 ?
mance.}{\fs20 \u8194\'20}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 \line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 How does the question concerning the mini}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0
mum amount of time needed to make a movement correction relate to the performance of motor skills in real-world situations? Knowing this time }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 limi}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2\u173 ?\u173 ?\u173 ?\u173 ?}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 tation for human performance becomes especially \line }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 relevant when we try to evaluate performance associated with sports skills and activities of daily living. For example, whether or not a person will have time to adjust his or her initial hand movement to catch a ball will depend on the amount of time available to catch the ball. If the ball speed is too fast or the distance the ball travels is too short to allow any movement modification, success at catching the ball will depend on the initial hand position. Similarly, if a person is stair climbing at a pace that is too fast to allow foot-position adjustments while the foot is in flight, the risk of falling increases.\par }
\pard\plain \s13\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb260\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Time to Contact: The Optical Variable }{\*\cs53\fs20\b\i\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\outl0 Tau}{\fs20  \par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 In situations in which a person moves toward an object to make contact with it, or the object moves toward the person, such as when a person is catching or hitting a thrown ball, vision plays an important role in specifying }
{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i when}{\fs20  to initiate the action and make contact with the object. The important visual information in these situations is the }
{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i time to contact,}{\fs20  which is the amount of time remaining until the object contacts the person (or vice versa) from a specific distance (see Bootsma & Peper, 1992). }
{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i Time to contact is specified according to the relative rate of change of the size of the image of the object on the retina of the eye.}
{\fs20  As the person approaches the object, or vice versa, the object produces an increasingly larger retinal image}{\fs20  at an increasingly larger rate of expansion}
{\fs20 . When this image attains a certain critical }{\fs20 rate of expansion}{\fs20 , it triggers the action required by the situation.\par }
\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 In the early 1970s, David Lee (1974) provided evidence that time to contact is specified by an \u173 ?optical variable, which he termed }
{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i tau}{\fs20  (}{\*\cs54\f6\fs20\b0\i0\u964 ?}{\fs20 ). He also showed that }{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i tau}{\fs20  can be quantified mathematically by relating object size, the distance of the object from the person, and the angle subtended at the person by the object size and distance. In mathematical terms, }
{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i tau}{\fs20  is the inverse of the relative rate of change of the visual angle subtended by the moving object, given the speed of approach of the object is constant. Since the publication of Lee\rquote s article, numerous motor control and learning researchers have investigated the role }
{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i tau}{\fs20  plays in controlling our actions and movements}{\fs20  (see Lee, 2009 and Lee \line et al., 2009 for summaries of this research)}
{\fs20 . \par The motor control bene}{\*\cs48\f9\fs20\b0\i0 \'de}{\fs20 t of the }{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i tau}{\fs20  variable is its predictive function, which allows action \u173 ?
initiation and object contact to occur \ldblquote automatically\rdblquote  at a speci}{\*\cs48\f9\fs20\b0\i0 \'de}{\fs20 c time to contact regardless of the speed of the object or person. When driving a car, for example, the driver\rquote s initiation and amount of braking \u173 ?
action to avoid collision with another car is not dependent on the driver\rquote s cognitive knowledge of the distance to and velocity of the other car. Rather, by specifying the time to contact at any distance and velocity, the rate of change of the size of the retinal image of the other car provides the information needed by the driver to \u173 ?
determine }{\fs20 \line }{\fs20 the type of braking, or deceleration, required by the situation. We will consider }{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i
tau}{\fs20  and its relation to specific \u173 ?motor skills in chapter 7.\par }\pard\plain \s18\f5\fs18\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li120\ri0\sb0\sa252\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\caps\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs18 Summary}{\fs18 \par }\pard\plain \s19\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi-170\li170\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 Touch, proprioception, and vision are important sources of feedback involved in movement control.\par }
\pard\plain \s19\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi-170\li170\ri0\sb98\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Touch provides the tactile sensory information that is important for the control of movement. Mechanoreceptors in the skin are the sensory receptors that provide this information by detecting skin stretch and joint movement. Research has shown that tactile feedback is important in motor control for influencing movement-related characteristics such as movement accuracy, movement consistency,}
{\fs20  }{\fs20 force adjustments for ongoing movements}{\fs20 ,}{\fs20  and for assisting \u173 ?proprioception in the estimation of movement distance.}
{\fs20 \par }{\fs20 Proprioception information is detected by pro\u8209 ?\line prioceptors located in the muscles, tendons, ligaments, and joint capsules. The muscle spindles are the most important receptors for providing the CNS with feedback about limb position, \u173 ?
direction, and velocity. The Golgi-tendon organs detect changes in muscle force. The joint receptors provide feedback about joint movement when the angular movement or joint positions are at their extreme limits.\par }
\pard\plain \s19\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi-170\li170\ri0\sb100\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 To investigate the role of proprioception in }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 motor control, researchers use several experimental techniques that remove or distort pro\u8209 ?}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 prioceptive feedback. The results of this research have established that proprioceptive feedback \u173 ?
influences several motor control functions, including movement accuracy, the timing of }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1
the onset of motor commands, and various aspects of the coordination of body and limb segments, such as postural control, the spatial-temporal coupling between limbs and limb segments, and adaptation to movement situations that require the use of nonpreferred coordination patterns.\par }
{\fs20 We tend to use and trust vision more than our other senses for information to control movement. Vision\rquote s dominant role as a source of sensory information is commonly observed in situations in which vision and proprioception provide conflicting information about characteristics of our movement, a phenomenon that was demonstrated in the }
{\fs20 \ldblquote moving room experiment.\rdblquote \par Vision results from sensory receptors in the eyes that receive wavelengths of light through structures such as the cornea, pupil, lens, and retina and transmit the information that reaches the retina to the visual cortex in the brain by way of the optic nerve.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s19\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi-170\li170\ri0\sb100\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 To investigate the role of vision in motor control, researchers use several experimental techniques, such as eye movement recording and the occlusion of temporal and event }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 (spatial) }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 information in a scene.\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 Research evidence has established that vision plays several important roles in motor control, such as providing depth perception for interacting with objects, other people, and our daily environment; providing information that enables us to identify objects, people, and other environmental context components; providing information that enables us to move through our environment; \u173 ?
coordinating movements involved in eye-hand coordination activities; and making movement corrections as we move.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2
\par }\pard\plain \s19\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi-170\li170\ri0\sb98\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Research evidence shows that the visual system is actually two anatomical and physiological systems. The vision-for-perception system allows us\u8239 ?
to recognize and describe what we see; the \u173 ?vision-for-action system allows us to move in our environment.}{\fs20 \par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2
In situations in which a person moves toward an object to make contact with it, or in which an \u173 ?object moves toward a person, the visual variable }
{\*\cs47\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw2 tau}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2  specifies the amount of time until contact. At a critical time}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2
 }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 to}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2  }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 contact, the motor control system initiates the action required in the situation.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 \par }\pard\plain \s20\f5\fs18\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li120\ri0\sb0\sa100\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\caps\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs18 Points for the Practitioner\par }\pard\plain \s21\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi-170\li170\ri0\sb152\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Because touch, proprioception, and vision are important for enabling people to carry out their daily living and recreational activities, it is important to determine how deficits in any of these sensory systems may explain difficulties a person may have performing a specific activity. Movement accuracy and coordination problems may be the result of sensory-related problems.\par }
{\fs20 People will typically use vision to substitute for touch and/or proprioception when they begin learning a skill that requires them to rely on touch and/or proprioception for successful perfor\u173 ?
mance, such as watching their fingers hit keyboard keys when learning to keyboard or play the piano, watching their hands when learning to dribble a ball, or watching their feet when learning a dance routine.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s21\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi-170\li170\ri0\sb144\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Make certain that a person\rquote s central vision (i.e., the point of gaze) is focused directly on an object that needs to be grasped or caught to ensure the successful achievement of the action goal.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s21\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi-170\li170\ri0\sb152\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 People can make movement corrections while performing a skill only when there is a sufficient amount of time to make the corrections. As a result, movement errors may be the result of movement or environmental context conditions that were too fast to allow a correction, even though the person knew he or she needed to make a movement adjustment. Examples include ball speed that is too fast to allow a correction of hand position to catch it or of bat or racquet position to hit it or a person moving too fast to correct a foot position or movement error when stepping over an obstacle in the pathway or on a stair step when ascending stairs.\par }
